<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870918-0107 </DOCNO><HL> Global Finance (A Special Report): Rankings---Tracking the Leaders:Japanese Companies Vault to the TopIn the Annual Survey of Global Firms</HL><DD> 09/18/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> IBM CCIFINANCIAL, INSURANCE, MUTUAL FUNDS, ACCOUNTING, LEASING (FIN)INSURANCE (INS)SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)BANKS, THRIFT INSTITUTIONS (BNK) </IN><TEXT>   JAPAN HAS captured much of the lead in rankings of the world's largest companies and financial institutions, displacing some traditional U.S. front-runners.    The world's 100 largest companies, for example, are headed this year by Nippon Telegraph andamp; Telephone Corp., which earlier this year became the most successful new issue in history. Last year's No. 1, International Business Machines Corp., slipped to second place. And among banks, Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank displaced Citicorp as the largest in terms of assets.    The Japanese ascendancy is just one of many patterns that emerge from The Wall Street Journal's second annual global rankings of companies and financial institutions. The surveys also highlight sweeping national differences in profitability and other financial data.    The list of the world's 100 largest public companies was prepared by Morgan Stanley Capital International Perspective in New York. Rankings of the world's 100 largest banks, 50 largest insurers and 25 largest securities and financial-services firms were compiled from the Worldscope data base. Worldscope is a joint venture of Wright Investors' Service Inc. and the Center for International Financial Analysis andamp; Research in Princeton, N.J.    For the 100 largest companies, rankings are as of June 30, using exchange rates prevailing at the time. Financial data are for fiscal 1986.    For the listings of financial institutions, rankings are based on data for fiscal 1986. Exchange rates are converted at year-end 1986 levels. Comparative data for fiscal 1985 has been recalculated, using year-end 1985 exchange rates.    By necessity, the rankings omit some closely held institutions, or financial subsidiaries of public companies, for which data is unavailable. Also excluded are most state-owned banks, quasi-government entities and savings banks, which aren't generally active internationally.    For investors, charts show how the world-wide bull market has benefited nearly all major stock exchanges, especially Japan's. Investors also will find that trading practices vary considerably, country to country (see accompanying illustration -- WSJ Sept. 18, 1987).    ---       As World Markets Grow, The U.S. Loses Its Lead                 Stock market capitalization                (In billions of U.S. dollars)                        July 31, 1987    U.S.                                        $2,839*    Japan                                       $2,654**    Other                                       $1,288    U.K.                                        $  710    West Germany                                $  252                        May 26, 1977    U.S.                                        $  775    Japan                                       $  178**    Other                                       $  128    U.K.                                        $   80    West Germany                                $   56    *NYSE only    **&quot;First Section&quot; only    Source: Morgan Stanley Capital International Perspective   ---          The World's 100 Largest Public Companies   Ranked by market value as of June 30, 1987, as determinedby Morgan Stanley Capital International Perspective   (In millions of U.S. dollars; financial data at Dec. 31,1986, exchange rates; percent change based on home currency)                           Fiscal   %Chg    Fiscal   %Chg      Rank     Market      1986     From    1986     From   1987  1986   Value      Sales@   1985    Profit   1985    NTT* (Japan)    1     --   $263,452    $31,819    9%    $1,164    -43%    IBM (U.S.)    2      1  